text: To all the people saying this is basically The Fault in Our Stars: instead of pointing out stupid similarities like, yeah they're ALL sick and probably someone will die, and they fall in love. But can't you simply enjoy the damn movie??? Can't you see the struggle??? They can't touch!!! Hazel and Augustus were able to hug, to kiss, to even hold hands, but Will and Stella??? They're not allowed to do that!! Damn, six feet apart from the person you're in love with can be one of the most painful things ever...  Augustus was "cancer free" (or at least, they thought he was), he "survived". The same with Isaac and Patrick, for example. They saved themselves, they won. But CF has no cure. Even if you get new lungs it will only give you a few more years. But not a normal life.  That's the issue here: they all know they won't survive CF. They all know that's their curse, their fate; die young, die too young because you're sick. And, as if being a walking corpse (that's probably how Will would call it) wasn't enough torture... They fall in love with their own death.   They have to choose between living as much as they can while their lungs are slowly dying... But apart.   Or living happy, enjoying the time they have left together and doing the one thing they're asking for.   Is it really living when you're not enjoying your life?? When you're still breathing bc if not, other ppl would be sad?? Devastated???   Is it really living if you only wake up because you HAVE to wake up??   And, of course, the real part of all this: why do these stories exist???   John Green met Esther Grace Earl years ago at a Harry Potter convention. They became friends, really good friends.  ...Esther died the 3 of August, when she was 16 years old and her lungs cancer won.  John Green wanted to give her a bit more, as Hazel would say, he wanted more numbers for Esther Grace Earl.   Justin met Claire Wineland via YouTube, I suppose: she was a youtuber, yeah. She posted videos about her life, about CF and about herself.   Claire was deeply in love with life. You'd never hear her trying to avoid the fact of dying, because she knew she wasn't going to live as much as her friends. Claire was pure and complete sweetness and positivity. You really should go and watch her videos.   Claire Wineland left us a couple months ago (sorry, can't remember the exact date). This is her legacy.   So please, stop comparing two beautiful women, two beautiful stories just to make Five Feet Apart look less important. I'm asking you as a reader, as a fan of them both and as a freakin' human being. You can't compare death to see if Claire's was more tragic than Esther's or vice versa. The same with the stories.

text: Another sob story about cancer patients falling in love and then dying. It's just The Fault In Our Stars all over again. The only thing about this movie's story is the question of which one dies first and it's disgusting. Want to cry over something that's really heartbreaking? Go to a children's hospital and see the 5-15 year olds with the same diseases that may never grow old enough to see this movie. These movies milk real illnesses and romanticise death and sickness as if it's 'fun' and not absolute hell. Give the money you would use for the movie ticket and donate it to a cancer research foundation or hospital where the money can be used for real people who are really dying instead of another greedy film corporation hellbent on milking the same old story for money.

text: I have CF. My concern with this movie is that it seems to be so heavily dramatizing the health of those of us with Cystic Fibrosis as if our entire lives are either spent 'throwing all caution to the wind' or living completely obsessed with CF every second of every day, as if the disease is what defines us as people.  Yes, I do 3 hours of treatments and take over 100 pills each day. Yes I spent my teenage years thinking I wouldn't live past 25. Yes I'll likely die decades earlier than my family and friends.   But all those things also made me a really interesting person with beautiful perspectives on life. I used all those hours doing treatments every day teaching myself skills so I now run my own business. I have an incredible and supportive wife and great friends. I am not my disease, and have a LOT to live for.     I'm really glad this film is bringing awareness to the disease (more awareness = more money for CF research = closer to a cure) but I'm afraid the heavy dramatization and romanticizing of two CF teens making really foolish decisions as if that's what it means to "live life fully" may just contribute to the idea that those of us with CF are nothing beyond our disease.   We will see.
author: C. Blake Davis

text: I have Cystic Fibrosis. Iâ€™m happy that the name Cystic Fibrosis is getting some awareness, but I highly doubt this movie will show any of yâ€™all what itâ€™s actually like to live with CF.  I, for one, havenâ€™t worn an oxygen tube since I was 6 years old. Iâ€™m going on 18 in a few months. Also, I havenâ€™t been hospitalized since I was 12 years old. Iâ€™m extremely healthy for what I have, and so I can live a near-normal life.  Treatments and pills are pretty standard. I take 50 pills every day, eat 5+ meals everyday, complete an hour of physical treatments everyday, and get regular cardio exercise in too.  What this movie wonâ€™t show you is the nasty side of CF. I canâ€™t tell you how many times Iâ€™ve been embarrassed by my disease. There have been times where Iâ€™ve been in social situations, coughed once or twice in my arm, only to pull it back and see that I just coughed up half a lungâ€™s worth in mucus. Iâ€™ve also had bathroom emergencies in public restrooms that are not unlike what the LA Beast went through when he ate gummy bears and kombucha (just look up LA Beast gummy bears and skip to the end of the video, and youâ€™ll see what I mean). Iâ€™ve also passed out in front of people during outdoor activities in the summer, because my cells reject 70-80% of the salt I take in, so I get dehydrated very easily. In fact, that is the root cause of CF, and is why my body produces so much mucus.  Itâ€™s not cute or romantic in any way, shape, or form. Also, I never go near any other CFers. In fact, if two CFers find out theyâ€™re closer than 6 feet apart from each other, they acknowledge it with a head-nod, and then run screaming in opposite directions.

text: SPOILER ALERT!!!      Just saw this movie today and man it hit me in the feels. First off, Poeâ€™s death was really really sad, though I could kinda tell it was coming when that nurse was slow to answering the door. I wish they wouldâ€™ve touched more on her reaction to that  When Stella steps onto the ice, my entire theater gasped for air, and I tell you, those next 5-10 minutes were so tense because we all knew what was gonna happen, but still they pulled it off so well. I like how they initially subverted expectations by them getting off, but then she falls off that little bridge thing, and even then, waited a little longer before going under. Well played movie.  Lastly, right after when Will saves Stella and gives her mouth to mouth, knowing that itâ€™d kill him was really touching. After the transplant and he gives her that book, and sets up the lights, as a straight dude, found it surprising that I was getting close to tears. I like the somewhat open ending where instead of showing Will straight up die, they just had him walk away.   A great movie imo, highly recommend for a date night, so guys, bring your girls and some tissues haha

Thankfully medicines have improved massively over the last 10 years in the UK and 'wonder drugs' have been provided to us. Everyday I feel thankful and blessed that we are both healthy. text: Ugh. Disease of the week movies. Why do we still have them? Hasn't the world-at-large worked it out yet? All illness is emotional negativity made physical. All well-being is emotional joy made physical. All death is fine, because there is no such thing as death, just a soul re-joining the non-physical, and all the attention humans give to things makes them grow, because all that is physical is called into being by attention being put upon a Thing. If you put lots of attention on diseases, you get more diseases and more people with diseases. If you put your attention on well-being and happy people, you see more well-being and happy people. The universe is composed of what we put our attention on most of the time. Does the human race still think wallowing around in a problem fixes a problem? There is not one iota of evidence that swirling in a problem fixes a problem, it only makes the problem grow. The only thing that makes the world better is putting attention on GOOD things, and on solutions. Seriously, this information has been 'out there' for at least 20 years, when is the dumb world going to catch on to these obvious truths? You put all your attention on young people having and dying of diseases, guess what you get? More young people getting and dying of diseases! D'uh. People. What a bunch of slow-learning dickheads.

text: Where i come from relationships are frowned upon, meaning that i can't visit her place or go out for movies and stuff either. We "went" for drives tho, and the closest we could get was to hold hands (or awkward but glad hugs!) , Which changed a week ago when i somehow managed to bring her to my place, i was home alone and up for the risk of getting caught since i had to move 6000 miles from her for studies, all i wanted was one day. It was a fun day, she was there for a few hours and we watched this movie, i didn't know what it was about (human touch! That I'd soon be missing, her's... The only one i need). Even after 3 years of the relationship, I was still nervous to hold her hand during the movie, But i did and she put her head on my shoulder after a while, it was like breathing for the first time. The movie ended and it left her quietly sobbing on my shoulder, asking me to stay. I held her in my arms and close wasn't close enough. Talked to her to calm her down and... She did, eventually. I held her face and kissed her forehead, we then kissed for the first time, told that her that we'll be fine and make it work, she kissed me again and i won't ever forget her lips, sweeter than cherry. It gets alone in here and not an hour goes by that i don't think about her, Sometimes when I'm walking, i look up at the sky and say to my self that at least were under the same sky. Anyways, the moral really is that "if you're able, touch him, touch her"
